{{for|the Danish footballer|Svend Nielsen (footballer)}} {{for|the Danish wrestler|Svend Nielsen (wrestler)}}
{{Infobox person | name = Svend Nielsen | image = Svend_Nielsen.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth year|1919}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death year and age|2013|1919}} | death_place = | nationality = Danish | other_names = | occupation = Architect, Architectural engineer | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Svend Nielsen''' (1919â2013) was a [[Denmark|Danish]] born [[architect]] and [[Architectural engineering|architectural engineer]]. Nielsen with his partner, Carl Johnson, founded the firm Johnson and Nielsen. Nielsen was influential in the construction of many important structures in Southern California, including the [[Discovery Cube Orange County|Discovery Cube]] in [[Orange County, California|Orange County]],<ref name="ocreg">{{cite news|last1=Earley|first1=Christopher|title=Newport engineer leaves mark on landscape|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/nielsen-513374-johnson-newport.html|accessdate=August 3, 2016|publisher=Orange County Register|date=August 23, 2013}}</ref> the [[Coussoulis Arena]] in [[San Bernardino, California|San Bernardino]] (notable for its "spider-like" exterior frame work) and, most famously, the [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|Forum]] in [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood, CA]], which was the first structure of its kind to be built without support pillars.<ref name="legacy">{{cite web|title=Svend H. Nielsen's Obituary on The Press-Enterprise|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/pe/obituary.aspx?pid=165203056|website=The Press-Enterprise|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> The engineering of the Forum was quite a feat as the structural design allowed no obstructed seats in the entire arena.
Within the City of [[Riverside, California|Riverside]], three separate structures have been declared City Landmarks, including the Set Free Thrift Store on 14th Street, the Riverside Office Supply Store on 14th Street (refaced in 2013) and a garage on Market Street (demolished for redevelopment in 2012). All of these structures feature [[Mid-century modern|Mid Century Modern style architecture]] that was indicative of Nielsen's Danish influences.<ref name="propview">{{cite web|title=Address search - City of Riverside, California|url=http://olmsted.riversideca.gov/propertyviewer/|website=olmsted.riversideca.gov}}</ref>
Nielsen also designed and engineered the Danish Lutheran Church and Cultural Center located in Yorba Linda, California,<ref name="legacy" /> the Bachelor Quarters for the U.S. Naval base in Long Beach<ref name="LAtimes">{{cite news|title=Naval Quarters to Be Finished in June|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-01-29/realestate/re-1746_1_naval-quarters|work=Los Angeles Times|date=January 29, 1989}}</ref> and over 5,000 other buildings.<ref name="ocreg" />
In addition to his work in architecture and engineering, Nielsen was one of the founding members of the California Seismic Review Board, which would generate the guidelines that would later become the foundation for Chapter 34, of the existing building and structures code.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.calstate.edu/cpdc/ae/review/documents/2003-2004.pdf|accessdate=8/3/2016}}</ref>
Most recently, [[Nielsen Pool House|Nielsen's own home]] in Riverside, California has been named a City of Riverside City of Riverside Landmark (City of Riverside Landmark #134). The unique home, fully designed and constructed by Nielsen himself, was completed in 1966 and is considered to be quintessentially representative of Mid Century Modern Architecture. Built on to a slope overlooking a lake on the 12th hole of the Victoria Country Club Golf Course, the home features large concrete columns, some as high as 20 feet, which support the home above the slope. However, the most notable feature of the home is its design, in which it is built entirely around an indoor swimming pool. The swimming pool room is over 2,000 square feet and features 20' tall ceilings and a retractable roof that opens to the sky.<ref name="meeting">{{cite web|title=Meeting of Cultural Heritage Board on 7/20/2016|url=https://riversideca.legistar.com/MeetingDetail.aspx?ID=496574&GUID=94075157-2898-4C06-BF96-20D22CFC9DD1&Options=info&Search=|website=City of Riverside|date=July 20, 2016}}</ref>
